\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 5.             Hugueninia}            Reichenb.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By P.W. Ball.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Perennial; hairs more or less stellate. Leaves 2-pinnatisect. Sepals not saccate at the base; petals yellow, exceeding the sepals. Fruit a siliqua; valves 1-veined; style very short; stigma slightly 2-lobed. Seeds c. 2 mm, not winged, mucilaginous when moistened.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. H. tanacetifolia} (L.) Reichenb., {\i Fl. Germ. Excurs.} 691 (1832) ({\i Sisymbrium tanacetifolium} L.). Stout, tomentose, pubescent or subglabrous perennial 30-70 cm. Lower leaves up to 30 cm, long-petiolate; segments 8-10 pairs, broadly linear to lanceolate, serrate to pinnatifid, the ultimate lobes 4-10 mm wide. Petals c. 4 mm. Siliqua 6-15 × 1·2-1·5 mm, oblong-oblanceolate, erecto-patent; valves with a strong mid-vein. Seeds c. 2 mm. •{\i  S.W. Alps, eastwards to c.} 7° 45' {\i E.; C. Pyrenees, mountains of N. Spain}. Ga He Hs It.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp.{\b  tanacetifolia} : Stem and lower surface of leaves grey pubescent or subglabrous; segments of the lower leaves with 4-8(-10) pairs of teeth or lobes. Pedicels 5-8 mm in fruit.{\i  S.W. Alps}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp.{\i  suffruticosa} (Coste & Soulié) P.W. Ball,{\i  Feddes Repert.}{\b  68}: 194 (1963): Stem and lower surface of leaves grey tomentose; segments of the lower leaves with 1-4(5) pairs of teeth or lobes. Pedicels 7-11 mm in fruit.{\i  Pyrenees and mountains of N. Spain}.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 6.            Alliaria}                  Scop.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By P.W. Ball.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Biennial, more rarely perennial; hairs unbranched. Basal leaves undivided. Sepals not saccate at the base; petals white. Fruit a siliqua; valves 3-veined; style distinct; stigma more or less entire. Seeds large (2·5-4·5 mm).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. A. petiolata} (Bieb.) Cavara & Grande,{\i  Boll. Orto Bot. Napoli}{\b  3}: 418 (1913) ({\i A. officinalis} Andrz. ex Bieb.,{\i  Sisymbrium alliaria} (L.) Scop.). Plant up to 120 cm, smelling of garlic when crushed. Leaves reniform to triangular-ovate, cordate, crenate to coarsely sinuate dentate, the basal long-petiolate. Pedicels 2·5-13 mm in fruit, about as thick as the siliqua. Petals 4-8(-9) mm. Siliqua 20-70 × 1·5-3·5 mm, patent or erecto-patent. 2n = 36, 42.{\i  Europe from about} 68°{\i  N. southwards, but rarer in the extreme south.} All except Az Bl Cr Fa Is Rs(N) Sa Sb.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 7.            Eutrema}                 R.Br.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By P.W. Ball.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Perennial; glabrous or with very sparse unbranched hairs. Basal leaves simple. Sepals not saccate at the base; petals white. Fruit a siliqua; valves 1-veined; style distinct; stigma slightly 2-lobed. Seeds large (c. 3 mm), winged.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. E. edwardsii} R. Br., {\i Chloris Melv.} 9 (1823). Plant 5-40 cm, rhizomatous. Basal leaves ovate to orbicular, broadly cuneate to cordate at the base, usually entire, long-petiolate; cauline leaves oblong-ovate to linear-lanceolate, cuneate, more or less sessile; all fleshy. Petals 2-4 mm. Siliqua 6-20 × 1·5-3 mm, linear or oblong, erecto-patent; style 0·25-0·9 mm. 2n = 42. {\i Arctic Europe}. Rs(N) Sb.
\par

