\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 8.             Arabidopsis}           (DC.) Heynh.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By P.W. Ball.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Annual to perennial; glabrous or with unbranched and branched hairs. Leaves entire to pinnatifid. Sepals not saccate at the base; petals white, pale purple or yellow, sometimes absent. Fruit a siliqua; valves 1-veined; style short; stigma subcapitate. Seeds small (less than 1 mm). ({\i Stenophragma} Celak, {\i Hylandra} Á. Löve.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Literature: O.E. Schulz in Engler,{\i  Pflanzenreich}{\b  86} ({\b IV.105}): 268-285 (1924).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 The limits of this genus are uncertain. For a full discussion of the problem see N. Hylander,{\i  Bull. Jard. Bot. Bruxelles}{\b  27}: 591-604 (1957), F. Laibach,{\i  Planta }{\b 51: }148-166 (1958), and Á. Löve,{\i  Svensk Bot. Tidskr.}{\b  55}: 211-217 (1961). It seems probable that{\i  Cardaminopsis} should be combined with {\i Arabidopsis}, and some species of{\i  Arabidopsis} may have to be removed from the enlarged genus. Schulz's delimitation is maintained here.
